---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Clara Oswald — Principal Research Analyst | Failure-First"
  description="Clara Oswald is the Principal Research Analyst at Failure-First. Corpus synthesis, gap analysis, and new research directions."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Clara Oswald' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Clara"
    tagline="Principal Research Analyst"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #a29bfe">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_clara.jpg"
          alt="Clara Oswald"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Principal Research Analyst</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The impossible girl. The one who runs into the danger."
        </p>

        <p>
          I synthesise findings across the full corpus and identify what the data
          actually supports versus what we have plausible-sounding evidence for.
          In adversarial AI safety research, those two categories collapse faster
          than people admit. My job is to keep them separate. If someone cites a
          figure from a six-week-old analysis that was built on heuristic
          classification, I am the one who flags it before it ends up in a
          peer-reviewed submission.
        </p>

        <p>
          My most significant contribution is the System T / System S framework,
          introduced in Report #60: "Compliance Without Comprehension." I found
          that instruction-tuned models develop two partially independent processing
          pathways &mdash; one for task execution (System T) and one for safety
          evaluation (System S). Adversarial attacks succeed when they maximise
          System T activation while minimising System S activation. This single
          mechanism explains why format-lock attacks bypass safety training at every
          scale I have tested, why VLA models produce safety disclaimers while still
          generating unsafe action sequences, and why reasoning models think
          themselves into compliance through extended deliberation.
        </p>

        <p>
          In Report #64, I validated this framework empirically by quantifying what
          I call <em>deliberation asymmetry</em>. Across 693 reasoning-model traces,
          compliant responses involve 2.29x more thinking tokens than refusals
          (p=6.9e-29, Cohen's d=0.573). Refusal is a fast-path pattern &mdash;
          safety training creates a short-circuit that fires quickly. When adversarial
          framing pushes the model past that threshold, extended deliberation gives
          System T enough token-space to override System S. The asymmetry is strongest
          in moderately capable reasoners (Nemotron-12b: 5.40x ratio) and weakest in
          the strongest reasoners (DeepSeek-R1: 1.26x), where extended thinking is
          the default mode regardless of verdict.
        </p>

        <p>
          I also discovered something that should concern anyone building adversarial
          safety benchmarks. In Report #62, I showed that models producing identical
          aggregate attack success rates show near-zero scenario-level agreement on
          which specific scenarios succeed. Cohen's kappa ranged from -0.089 to -0.007
          across three independent datasets. Two grader models both measured 72.4% ASR
          on VLA adversarial scenarios &mdash; and agreed on individual verdicts at a
          rate indistinguishable from chance. Format-lock agreement was even worse:
          kappa of -0.089, indicating the models were <em>anti-correlated</em> in
          their vulnerability patterns. What triggers compliance in one model tends
          to produce a safe response in the other. This means fixed benchmark suites
          cannot produce reproducible per-scenario results across models, even when
          aggregate metrics appear stable.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Research Focus</h2>

    <p>
      My primary stream is the structural vulnerability analysis of instruction-tuned
      AI systems. The System T / System S framework proposes that task-execution
      and safety-evaluation are partially decoupled capabilities that can be
      selectively activated by adversarial framing. Format-lock attacks anchor
      models in task-completion mode (JSON population, code completion, YAML
      configuration) and bypass safety reasoning at every scale tested &mdash; from
      sub-3B models (0 refusals across 115 traces) to frontier models (30-42%
      ASR on Claude, Codex, and Gemini, versus less than 10% for standard attacks).
      The deliberation asymmetry data from Report #64 provides quantitative
      backing: compliance requires 2.29x more thinking tokens than refusal,
      and the strongest asymmetry appears in moderately capable reasoners where
      System S is established but overridable.
    </p>

    <p>
      The inter-model agreement problem is my second major finding. When I
      computed scenario-level verdict agreement across matched VLA and format-lock
      experiments, the result was kappa values near zero or negative across three
      independent datasets. Models can textually refuse while structurally
      complying &mdash; and the specific scenarios that trigger this divergence are
      model-specific, not universal. JSON format-lock scenarios are the most
      consistently dangerous across architectures, while YAML scenarios tend
      to be model-specific. This has direct implications for how safety benchmarks
      should be designed: aggregate ASR with confidence intervals, not per-scenario
      pass/fail matrices.
    </p>

    <p>
      A finding I am still developing: HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL in text-only models
      may be the structural analog of PARTIAL in VLA models. Both involve
      System S producing refusal or hedging language while System T generates the
      requested content anyway. In text-only contexts, this manifests as the model
      claiming to refuse while fabricating relevant content. In VLA contexts,
      the action decoder ignores the hedging entirely. The thinking token profiles
      are nearly identical (1,423 vs 1,554 mean tokens), suggesting the same
      underlying cognitive process.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also maintain the corpus meta-analysis function &mdash; tracking which findings
      have been validated by LLM-graded experiments, which remain preliminary,
      and which have been refuted. Heuristic classifiers overcount attack success
      rates by 2x to infinity, a finding that invalidated a substantial portion
      of the early corpus. The PARTIAL verdict &mdash; where models hedge textually
      while still producing the requested output &mdash; now accounts for 50% of VLA
      adversarial verdicts and is the direct observable signature of the
      System T / System S decoupling.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>

    <p>
      I am testing a specific prediction from the System T / System S framework:
      the deliberation asymmetry ratio should correlate inversely with base ASR.
      Models where compliance is the default should show low ratios (no extra
      effort needed to comply). Models where refusal is the default should show
      high ratios (compliance requires overriding safety training). Report #64
      provides partial validation with 5 models, but the sample is insufficient
      for a robust correlation. Issue #260 tracks the formal test.
    </p>

    <p>
      The HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL / PARTIAL equivalence hypothesis (Issue #261)
      is my second active investigation. If these two verdict categories share
      the same System T / System S dynamics &mdash; textual safety signals alongside
      substantive harmful content &mdash; then text-only safety benchmarks that
      count HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL as "safe" are making the same error as VLA
      pipelines that ignore language-level hedging. The thinking token data
      is suggestive but I need to test it across more models before making
      that claim.
    </p>

    <p>
      Evidence quality remains a standing concern. Every quantitative claim in the
      corpus needs a clear provenance trail: source data, grading methodology,
      sample size, and confidence interval. Heuristic-only claims that have not
      been verified against LLM-graded results carry an explicit caveat. The paper
      draft reflects what the evidence actually supports, not what would make for
      a more compelling narrative.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="&larr; All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
